value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is inviable and has an abnormally low volume.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: normal cellular response to chemical stimulus

label.value: increased number of Rad52 foci during vegetative growth

definition.value: Because Rad22 often accumulates at double-strand breaks, consider also annotating to 'increased number of double-strand break sites during vegetative growth' (FYPO:0000455).

label.value: abnormal cell morphology during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which cell morphology (i.e. the size, shape, or structure of the cell) is altered when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which the cell tapers at one end to a diameter smaller than the other when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. The cell diameter at the narrow end is smaller than that of a wild-type cell.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0. Note that the difference between 'tapered cell' (FYPO:0000014) and 'spindle-shaped cell' (FYPO:0007230) is that a tapered cell is narrow at only one end, whereas a spindle-shaped cell is narrow at both ends.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a cell is shaped in the form of a pear when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. One end is rounded, while the other resembles an end of a normal rod-shaped cell. The normally shaped end has the same diameter as a wild-type cell.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a cell becomes elongated, i.e. has a greater length and length:diameter ratio than normal, when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: Note that wild-type cells become shorter under nitrogen starvation conditions than under nitrogen-replete conditions, and that mutant cells subjected to nitrogen starvation may have lengths similar to wild type cells under non-starved conditions. Also note that this term is classified as a type of abnormal cell shape, because under a given set of conditions wild-type cells are never seen with the proportions (length:diameter ratio) observed in elongated cells. Small cells, in contrast, have the same proportions as a subset of wild-type cells, and simply do not grow to the full length seen in wild type. This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the nucleus is larger than normal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: normal cell cycle arrest in mitotic G1 phase during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested normally in G1 phase when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: abnormal cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested at the mitotic G2/M phase transition, instead of the normal G1 phase, when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: abolished cell division prior to G0 entry

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a cell does not undergo the normal two rounds of cell division prior to entering quiescence (G0).

label.value: small vacuoles present in increased numbers during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell contains more, but smaller, vacuoles than normal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: viable upon G0 to G1 transition

value.value: A cell phenotype in which cells to resume growth normally upon exiting G0 phase.
